Vheadline
p2
VOn a winning note
p3
sVnews
p4
VAt a grand function organised at Gokaraju Laila Gangaraju Kala Vedika, Government Music College premises, Vijayawada, awards were presented to the winners of Annual Akashvani Music competitions in Carnatic music held this year. After a long gap Vijayawada Akashvani got the opportunity to stage the awards function.The awards included a memento, cash prize and a certificate. They were given away to the young and deserving winners by veteran vidwan Annavarapu Ramaswamy. It was heartening to see that all the young winners of the Akashvani competition are extremely talented.The concerts of the winners began with a fine vocal concert by A. Narayanan of Chennai, the first prize winner. He sported a sharp, clear and felicitous voice starting withMamava sada jananiin Kanada. Next, Narayanan sangMarivere(Shanmukhapriya) of Patnam which was the main piece of the concert. He closed the concert withVuyyalalugavayyain Neelambari. He was supported well by B.V. Durgabhavani on violin, B.V.S. Prasad on mridangam and Rohit Prasad on morsing.Second prize winner Tanmayi of Bangalore sang next renderingChesinadella marachitivoin Todi as the main item adorning the keertana with fine alapana, detailed niraval and efficient swaras. Good support on violin and mridangam was provided by Bhavani and K. Sadgurucharan respectively. Tanmayi&#8217;s concluding item was a Purandaradas keertana in Sama.Sudha R.S. Iyer of Chennai, first prize winner in violin, presented a melodious violin solo showing exceptional talent. She playedSankari Samkuruin Saveri of Syamasastri which carried impressive raga, niraval and swara kalpana. A scintillating thillana in Mand was Sudha&#8217;s concluding item. The tala vadya kacheri participated by Rohit Prasad of Mumbai (first prize in mridangam) and G. Chandrasekhara sarma of Chennai (first prize winner in ghatam) was a fine treat in laya vinyasam.P. Naga Sahiti of Hyderabad, first prize winner in light music, renderedOka pata padana,OkasariandSakhiya ravela.Sahiti&#8217;s voice was melodious and her modulation was perfect. Modumudi Sudhakar of Akashvani conducted Sagutu&#8217;s programme with instrumental support from Palaparthy Nageswara rao (violin), Anjaneyulu (keyboard), Imam Saheb (clarinet), P.K.M. Sarma (flute) and L. Prabhakar (tabla).
